VALUES ('chk_ch05_0145', 'src_ch05', 'Persecution under Diocletian | Diocletian | | **c. 311â€“411 AD** | The Donatist Schism divides the African Church | Donatus Magnus, Circumcellions | | **354 AD** | Augustine born in Thagaste (Souk Ahras, Algeria) | Augustine, Monica (mother) | | **386 AD** | Augustine''s conversion in Milan (*tolle, lege*) | Augustine, Ambrose | | **391â€“396 AD** | Augustine ordained priest, then Bishop of Hippo Regius (Annaba) | Augustine | | **397 AD** | Council of Carthage confirms NT canon (27 books) |', 144, NULL);
INSERT INTO RAG_Chunks (id, source_id, chunk_text, chunk_index, embedding_key)
VALUES ('chk_ch05_0146', 'src_ch05', '| Augustine | | **397 AD** | Council of Carthage confirms NT canon (27 books) | Augustine | | **396â€“430 AD** | Augustine serves as Bishop of Hippo Regius | Augustine | | **410 AD** | Sack of Rome by Visigoths (prompting *City of God*) | Augustine | | **418 AD** | Council of Carthage condemns Pelagianism | Augustine | | **429 AD** | Vandal invasion under Gaiseric (80,000 people) | Gaiseric | | **430 AD** | Augustine dies during Vandal siege of Hippo | Augustine | | **439 AD** | Vandals capture', 145, NULL);
INSERT INTO RAG_Chunks (id, source_id, chunk_text, chunk_index, embedding_key)
VALUES ('chk_ch05_0147', 'src_ch05', 'Augustine dies during Vandal siege of Hippo | Augustine | | **439 AD** | Vandals capture Carthage, establish Arian kingdom | Gaiseric | | **429â€“534 AD** | Vandal Kingdom rules from Carthage (Arian persecution) | Gaiseric, Victor of Vita | | **533â€“534 AD** | Byzantine reconquest under Belisarius | Justinian I, Belisarius | | **534â€“698 AD** | Byzantine (Eastern Roman) rule | Justinian I | | **c. 640â€“710 AD** | Islamic conquest of North Africa | | | **642 AD** | Arab conquest of Byzantine', 146, NULL);
INSERT INTO RAG_Chunks (id, source_id, chunk_text, chunk_index, embedding_key)
VALUES ('chk_ch05_0148', 'src_ch05', '| Islamic conquest of North Africa | | | **642 AD** | Arab conquest of Byzantine Egypt | | | **647 AD** | First major Islamic raids into Tripolitania | | | **c. 686 AD** | Christian Berber king Kusaila killed in battle against Arabs | Kusaila | | **c. 702 AD** | Berber queen Kahina killed, Berber resistance collapses | Kahina | | **698 AD** | Final fall of Carthage to Arab forces; Kairouan founded | Hasan ibn al-Nu''man | | **c. 710 AD** | Islamic conquest reaches Atlantic (Morocco) | | ###', 147, NULL);
INSERT INTO RAG_Chunks (id, source_id, chunk_text, chunk_index, embedding_key)
VALUES ('chk_ch05_0149', 'src_ch05', 'ibn al-Nu''man | | **c. 710 AD** | Islamic conquest reaches Atlantic (Morocco) | | ### Review Questions **Short Answer:** 1. What were the key administrative divisions of Roman North Africa, and why was the region known as the "breadbasket of Rome"? 2. Who was Simon of Cyrene (Mark 15:21), and what is the theological significance of his role in the crucifixion story? 3. According to the book of Acts, what multiple biblical connections exist between Cyrene and the spread of the Gospel (Acts 2:10,', 148, NULL);
INSERT INTO RAG_Chunks (id, source_id, chunk_text, chunk_index, embedding_key)
VALUES ('chk_ch05_0150', 'src_ch05', 'Acts, what multiple biblical connections exist between Cyrene and the spread of the Gospel (Acts 2:10, 6:9, 11:20, 13:1)? 4. What was the central issue of conflict between the early Christians and the Roman authorities regarding emperor worship? 5. Name the three Councils of Carthage mentioned in this chapter and explain the significance of each (256, 397, 418 AD). 6. Who were the *traditores*, and how did they lead to the Donatist Schism? What was the geographic dimension of this schism? 7.', 149, NULL);
INSERT INTO RAG_Chunks (id, source_id, chunk_text, chunk_index, embedding_key)
VALUES ('chk_ch05_0151', 'src_ch05', 'did they lead to the Donatist Schism? What was the geographic dimension of this schism? 7. Name three major written works by Augustine of Hippo and describe their basic themes. 8. What was the primary religious difference between the Vandal rulers and the majority of the North African Christians they conquered? What biblical passages refute the Vandal position? 9. Who were Kusaila and Kahina, and what role did they play in resisting the Islamic conquest? 10. According to this chapter, what was', 150, NULL);
INSERT INTO RAG_Chunks (id, source_id, chunk_text, chunk_index, embedding_key)
VALUES ('chk_ch05_0152', 'src_ch05', 'role did they play in resisting the Islamic conquest? 10. According to this chapter, what was the fundamental reason the North African church disappeared while the Egyptian Coptic church survived? **Critical Essay Prompts:** 1. **Cross-Bearer and Church-Bearer**: Analyze the connection between Simon of Cyrene carrying Christ''s cross (Mark 15:21) and the role of the North African church in "bearing" theology to the Western world. How is this a prophetic picture? (150-250 words) 2. **African', 151, NULL);
INSERT INTO RAG_Chunks (id, source_id, chunk_text, chunk_index, embedding_key)
VALUES ('chk_ch05_0153', 'src_ch05', '"bearing" theology to the Western world. How is this a prophetic picture? (150-250 words) 2. **African Agency in the Roman Empire**: Compare and contrast the roles of Septimius Severus (African Roman Emperor who persecuted Christians) and Augustine (African bishop who shaped Christian theology). What does this tell us about the relationship between ethnicity, political power, and spiritual allegiance? (150-250 words) 3. **The Councils of Carthage**: Explain why the Council of Carthage in 397 AD,', 152, NULL);
INSERT INTO RAG_Chunks (id, source_id, chunk_text, chunk_index, embedding_key)
VALUES ('chk_ch05_0154', 'src_ch05', '(150-250 words) 3. **The Councils of Carthage**: Explain why the Council of Carthage in 397 AD, which confirmed the 27-book New Testament canon, is one of the most important events in Christian history. How does this challenge the modern perception of North Africa''s role in Christianity? (150-250 words) 4. **Donatism and Unity**: The Donatist schism illustrated the tension between doctrinal purity and church unity. Evaluate both sides of the debate. Was Augustine''s position (sacraments valid *ex', 153, NULL);
INSERT INTO RAG_Chunks (id, source_id, chunk_text, chunk_index, embedding_key)
VALUES ('chk_ch05_0155', 'src_ch05', 'purity and church unity. Evaluate both sides of the debate. Was Augustine''s position (sacraments valid *ex opere operato*) biblically sound? How does this debate relate to modern church divisions? (200-300 words) 5. **Why the Church Fell**: Analyze the three factors identified in this chapter for the disappearance of the North African church: (1) division (Donatism), (2) failure to indigenize (no Berber translation), and (3) isolation. Which factor was most significant, and why? Compare this to', 154, NULL);
INSERT INTO RAG_Chunks (id, source_id, chunk_text, chunk_index, embedding_key)
VALUES ('chk_ch05_0156', 'src_ch05', '(no Berber translation), and (3) isolation. Which factor was most significant, and why? Compare this to the survival of the Coptic church in Egypt. (250-350 words) 6. **"The Blood of the Martyrs is the Seed of the Church"**: Based on the events in this chapter (Scillitan Martyrs, Perpetua & Felicitas, Cyprian), was Tertullian''s statement accurate for the African church in the short term and the long term? Discuss both the positive impacts of persecution on church growth and the negative', 155, NULL);
INSERT INTO RAG_Chunks (id, source_id, chunk_text, chunk_index, embedding_key)
VALUES ('chk_ch05_0157', 'src_ch05', 'the long term? Discuss both the positive impacts of persecution on church growth and the negative long-term consequences. (200-300 words) ### Synthesis & Scripture The story of ancient North Africa is deeply interwoven with the biblical narrative. The region was associated in the Hebrew Scriptures with the descendants of **Phut** (Genesis 10:6), one of the sons of Ham. The presence of Cyrenian Jews at **Pentecost** (Acts 2:10) marks a pivotal moment where the Gospel explicitly intersects with', 156, NULL);
INSERT INTO RAG_Chunks (id, source_id, chunk_text, chunk_index, embedding_key)
VALUES ('chk_ch05_0158', 'src_ch05', 'Cyrenian Jews at **Pentecost** (Acts 2:10) marks a pivotal moment where the Gospel explicitly intersects with this land. But it goes deeper: a North African man, **Simon of Cyrene**, bore the very cross of Christ (Mark 15:21), a prophetic picture of the African church bearing the weight of Christian theology to the world. "Men of Cyrene" were pioneers in preaching to the **Gentiles** (Acts 11:20), and **Lucius of Cyrene** was a prophet and teacher in the influential church of Antioch (Acts', 157, NULL);
INSERT INTO RAG_Chunks (id, source_id, chunk_text, chunk_index, embedding_key)
VALUES ('chk_ch05_0159', 'src_ch05', 'and **Lucius of Cyrene** was a prophet and teacher in the influential church of Antioch (Acts 13:1). Reflect on how the rise of a powerful, Latin-speaking, theologically sophisticated church in North Africaâ€”a region once on the geographic periphery of Israel''s storyâ€”fulfills the prophetic vision of a faith that transcends ethnic and geographic boundaries (Isaiah 49:6: "I will make you as a light for the nations, that my salvation may reach to the end of the earth"). North Africa was not a', 158, NULL);
INSERT INTO RAG_Chunks (id, source_id, chunk_text, chunk_index, embedding_key)
VALUES ('chk_ch05_0160', 'src_ch05', 'that my salvation may reach to the end of the earth"). North Africa was not a late addition to the Christian story; from Pentecost onward, it was **central**. The North African church gave the world the **biblical canon** (Council of Carthage, 397 AD), the vocabulary of the **Trinity** (Tertullian), the theology of **grace** (Augustine), and the doctrine of the **church** (Cyprian). The fall of this great church is a sobering reminder that **faithfulness must be renewed in every generation**.', 159, NULL);
INSERT INTO RAG_Chunks (id, source_id, chunk_text, chunk_index, embedding_key)
VALUES ('chk_ch05_0161', 'src_ch05', 'of this great church is a sobering reminder that **faithfulness must be renewed in every generation**. Yet even in its fall, God''s providence preserved its legacy. The texts of Augustine, copied by faithful monks, crossed the sea and fueled the Reformation. The testimony of the martyrs still inspires. And the warning of North Africa''s failureâ€”its division, its failure to translate the Gospel into the heart language of the peopleâ€”remains urgent for the global church today. ', 160, NULL);

